      {
        "number": 3,
        "title": "Proportionality and the body — the lex talionis and slave-injury manumission",
        "range": "21:18-27",
        "excerpt": "But if there is any further injury, then you shall appoint as a penalty life for life, eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand for hand, foot for foot.",
        "body": "The chapter's middle movement develops the principle of proportional justice through assault cases that increase in complexity: the quarreling men (vv. 18-19), the beaten slave (vv. 20-21), the pregnant woman struck in a brawl (vv. 22-25), and the slave injured by the master (vv. 26-27). The lex talionis of vv. 23-25 is the section's organizing principle, but its meaning has been consistently distorted by reading it as a private-vengeance formula.\n\nIn the ancient Near East, the dominant pattern for inter-personal violence was unlimited escalation — the pattern Lamech boasts about in Genesis 4:23-24 ('I have killed a man for wounding me, a young man for striking me; if Cain is avenged sevenfold, then Lamech seventy-sevenfold'). The lex talionis is not an advancement of this logic; it is a categorical refutation of it. The penalty may be exactly proportionate to the harm, no more. It is a judicial ceiling, not a floor. As John Calvin (*Commentary on the Pentateuch*, 1563) observed, the formula's purpose is 'to restrain the fierce outrage of human passions' by imposing a legal maximum. This is why Jesus in Matthew 5:38-39 does not abolish the lex talionis as a judicial principle — he transcends it as a personal ethic. The two levels of application (judicial and personal) are distinct throughout the Sermon on the Mount.\n\nThe pregnant woman case (vv. 22-25) is one of the most discussed passages in debates about the legal status of the unborn. The text distinguishes two outcomes: if men fighting strike a pregnant woman and there is 'no injury' (*ason*), a fine is levied at the husband's demand (v.22); if there IS serious injury (*ason*), the full lex talionis applies — life for life (v.23). The category of ason extends to both the mother and the child. Most evangelical scholars (Gleason Archer, John Frame) read *ason* as covering harm to both, meaning that injury to the unborn child is subject to the same proportionality standard as injury to the mother. The text treats the unborn child as a nephesh — a life — protected by the same principle that protects any other human being.\n\nThe slave-injury cases of vv. 26-27 apply the proportionality principle in a surprising direction. The master does not lose his own eye or tooth in kind — he loses the slave's service entirely. The slave is freed. This is one of the ancient world's most striking slave-protection mechanisms: the master's economic interest in the slave is used as the lever of justice. Destroying even the smallest part of the slave's body — a single tooth — costs the master his entire investment. The lex talionis, which normally operates as a ceiling on penalty, here becomes a floor of human dignity: even the slave's tooth is worth more than it costs the master to ignore.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ason* (injury, vv. 22, 23) — harm, mishap, disaster; the same rare word used in Genesis 42:4, 38 of Jacob's fear for Benjamin's safety. *Nephesh* (life, v.23) — the whole living person; 'life for life' means the full personal existence is what is at stake. *Tachat* (for, vv. 23-25) — under, in place of; the preposition of substitution that makes the lex talionis a formula of equivalence."
      },
      {
        "number": 4,
        "title": "Knowledge creates accountability — negligence liability in the ox-goring and pit cases",
        "range": "21:28-36",
        "excerpt": "If, however, an ox was previously in the habit of goring and its owner has been warned, yet he does not confine it and it kills a man or a woman, the ox shall be stoned and its owner also shall be put to death.",
        "body": "The chapter's final movement addresses indirect liability — harm caused not by direct human violence but by the owner's failure to manage a known hazard. The governing principle is that prior knowledge creates moral responsibility. This is one of the Torah's most sophisticated contributions to the history of jurisprudence.\n\nThe basic goring-ox case (v.28) establishes the default: a first-time incident kills someone, the ox is stoned (removing a dangerous animal from the community), but the owner bears no penalty. This is not indifference to the victim; it is the recognition that the owner could not have anticipated what he had no reason to expect. But once the animal's behavior is known — 'previously in the habit of goring' (the Hebrew idiom *temol shilshom*, literally 'yesterday and the day before,' indicating established pattern) — and the owner has been warned, the calculus changes entirely. If the ox kills again, the owner is liable to death (v.29). The animal's second attack is the owner's first murder, because he knew what the ox would do and chose not to prevent it.\n\nThe ransom provision of v.30 introduces the kopher — the redemption payment that can substitute for the owner's life. The word belongs to the same semantic field as kaphar (to atone, to cover), and its appearance here in a judicial context is theologically suggestive. A life owed can be covered by a payment — but only if the victims' family demands it; justice is not automatically merciful. The thirty-shekels-of-silver payment for a slave killed by a goring ox (v.32) will echo through the canon in ways the Sinai legislation could not have anticipated. Zechariah 11:12-13 uses thirty pieces of silver as the insulting price put on the rejected Shepherd; Matthew 26:15 applies Zechariah's language to the betrayal of Jesus. The slave's blood-price becomes the price paid for the Son of God — an irony the New Testament handles with theological intentionality.\n\nThe uncovered-pit cases (vv. 33-36) extend the negligence principle from persons to animals. The man who digs a pit and fails to cover it is responsible for any animal that falls in — because the hazard is one he created and could have prevented. The ox-fights-ox case (vv. 35-36) applies the same prior-knowledge criterion: if the ox's dangerous habit was known and the owner failed to confine it, he bears full liability (ox for ox); if it was unknown, losses are shared equally. The chapter ends where it began — with a system of justice calibrated not merely by the act but by what the actor knew beforehand. In the language of Calvin's commentary, 'God holds us accountable not only for what we have done but for what we could have prevented.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kopher* (ransom, v.30) — cognate of *kaphar*, the atonement root of Leviticus. *Sheqel keseph* (shekels of silver, v.32) — the standardized commercial weight; thirty shekels is the value established in Leviticus 27:4 for a female person between 20-60, and the same sum Judas accepts. *Salem* (make restitution, vv. 34, 36) — the root of *shalom*, peace, wholeness; restitution aims at restoring wholeness, not merely penalizing the offender. *Temol shilshom* (previously in the habit, vv. 29, 36) — the Hebrew idiom for established past behavior, literally 'yesterday and the day before.'"
      }
